<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9765737517894></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9765737517894><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=9765737517894>Leveling 16-24</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=9765737517894#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=475><span id= >Artannis</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Dec 11th 10:29 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hello again everyone.  Sorry it's been so long to post this one, but for the 6 months that I have had EverQuest.  I wasn't playing it for three and a half of them.  I hope that you all didn't forget me.  If you haven't already read my level 1-16 posting, I suggest you do that first.  We left off at Erud's crossing.  It is best to go to Qeynos and get your level 16 spells now, including invisibility.  Yes!  Flame Shock will prove to be very useful to you.  This should become your primary attacking spell.  You will almost never need Bolt of Lightning.  Shock of fire does about 12 less damage than it, but it costs far less mana.  Not to mention that it's more precise.  With bolt spells, you have to be on equal or above ground with nothing between you and your target.  This is a direct damage spell and will hit the target if they are inside of a tent, etc.  While you're in Qeynos, pick up some Cat's Eye Agate.  This is a needed spell component for the spell, shield skin.  It absorbs a lot of damage without you taking any, and it is one of the most useful spells, so far.  Your next destination will be LakeRathetear.  There is a man somewhere in the Qeynos hills I think that talks about it.  Go there.  This is a suitable battle ground right up to 24.  There are numerous rumors of a monster in the water.  Don't worry about it.  Watch out for some freshwater sharks though.  The best thing to do here for a little while is fight the monk named Jonah who lives in a secluded part of the lake.  You may want to fight here with a partner for the first two levels or so.  He has about 350 hit points or so and hits twice a round for up to 32 damage a pop.  M-A-K-E  S-U-R-E  Y-O-U  <br>R-O-O-T  H-I-M  F-I-R-S-T.  If you do not he will kick you around mercilessly and slaughter you.  If your root fails, cast it again.  Then cast, Flame Shock on him until he dies.  You get no faction hits for killing hi what-so-ever, so don't worry.  For further information on battles, please go check out my "How to Battle Using a Wizard" which is also posted in this class strategy section.  Compare this with your own notes, and if your strategy works better, by all means, use it.  Wizards are hard to solo, and the best way to fight is to learn through experience.  Once you get to level 18, it is time for you to ascend to fight new enemies.  You should now try fighting Aviak Guards.  Careful not to lure too many at a time.  These guards also give you no faction hits, nor the smaller Aviaks near arena, and they only aggro against "evil" races.  It is still a good idea to group when you fight.  See if you can't group with another wizard near the same level.  This way, you can trade off casting on it.  If one of you hits it, it will attack them, get the other to cast on it, then it will go after that person, continue this till it dies.  You sustain little damage and it dies fast.  You could do also use the well known the rooting strategy too.  Rooting it, then nuking it.  Either one of these will work.  But if your root fails, you will lose the surprise attack and will of wasted valuable damaging mana.  Aviak Guards are excellent for experience points an you will level to 20 in short time.  As you progress, you should be getting at least one bubble of experience per hour.  If not, you should try with fewer group members, or to kill more enemies.  If neither of these work for various reasons, then just go with it for a little while.  Once I achieved level 19, I was able to solo at the area spawn.  It is the best place to camp in all of the lake for experience good because there are two Aviak guards there, and you won't pull them both if you hit one.  Not to mention, if you get in trouble, you can just run back into the cave and zone into arena.  It's as simple as that.  Once you get to 20, leave the lake for a little while.  You character is 4 levels stronger, so you deserve a little break.  Unless you have a better ear item than this, I suggest that you go back to Qeynos and into the sewer systems to find Cuburt.  He will drop a bloody dress which you can eventually get a golden ear stud for.  +3 int.  Research the quest first and go to EQatlas.com to get a detailed map on the subject.  It is very useful and helps you avoid the necromancer guild and the Spectres.  While you're down there.  Go invisible.  You'll be safe that way, except from the undead.  Make sure you con the undead before walking right in front of it.  If it's not in an aggressive mood you can continue.  Although, it shouldn't be necessary, to go near them, in the first place.  Go, next to your hometown to purchase your spells, as you will notice that they are getting more expensive.  It's cheaper to buy things in your home city, and this way you don't forget your roots.  Pfft.  Like it matters.  Anyway, memorize all of the spells, and do whatever else you want to do while you're there.  When you are finished, it is now time to return to Lake Rathetear.  You should be more than powerful enough to solo a guard and still get enough experience from it to level up to 24.  Just root them and nuke them.  You should be able to kill them with ease.  However, your mana may be almost depleted.  But hey, that's what meditation is for.  You know what to do.<br><br>Oh!  I almost forgot.  While you're there, take advantage of the zone.  There is a Gnoll embalmer there that you can loot the skull of Jhen'tra from.  He should be easy enough to kill once at 20.  Practice your swimming!  It's not like there's no water around!  Sense Heading is also a good thing to work on while Meditating.  Fishing is also an excellent idea here.  The friendly Ogres near the entrance to the Rathe Mountains will provide you with bait and a pole.  You can only buy from the female Ogre inside the stone hut.  One more thing.  Before you go back to Qeynos, pick up some Bandit Sashes from the bandits who are opposite of the Ogres.  You can trade them in to someone in the Paladin's guild, and get some experience, faction, and an item, which is worth over one platinum.<br><br>I hope that this was very helpful to everyone.  Please feel free to e-mail me at mikekoffler@sk.sympatico.ca with any questions or mistakes I may have made and I will comply.<br><br>Artannis<br>High Elven<br>Wizard of Tunare<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"People will belive any lie either because they want it to be true, or they're arfaid it's true."<br></td></tr>
