	   <tr><td colspan=2>I will agree with you to a certain point.  But you must realize what are the actual strengths and weaknesses to a wizard.  I want to quote from the "Everquest Ruins of Kunark" manual.  This is in their general decription of a wizard.<br><br>"A thirst for arcane knowledge has made her a master of defense, as well as an offensive force of destruction."<br><br>What catches my eye is the "Master of Defense" remark.  What they are talking about is that we are given many spells that greatly improve our resistances to the various magical attacks.  When we die we usually do not die because of some kind of magic spell being casted upon us, unless we have run upon a caster mob that is several levels higher than we are.  We die because of direct physical attacks that break up our casting.<br><br>Many people tell me about using a SOW or Journeyman Boots and kiting a mob.  But all of those people tell me that the only time they DO die is when they are unable to run away easily.  Such as in a dungeon where running is difficult,  if not impossible. to do without creating huge trains that kill everyone.  Unrest, Splitpaw, and Lower Guk would be good examples of such places.  Since difficult dungeons are often where you must go for most quest items.  That means that kiting is not really an option there.<br><br>My simple trading of a few INT for alot of AGI gives me the ability to become more self sufficient in groups and makes soloing easier.  Everyone, even the smartest and best of us out there, has been attacked by a spawn that happened at a poor time and died.  This agility gives us the ability to have a greater chance of surviving such an attack.  But please, continue to discuss this with me.  I draw upon others input to try to plan my setups.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
